title: Improve load time of anomalies page by 2x
body:
1. Refactoring: Move methods, MergedAnomalyResultBean and convertMergedAnomalyBean2DTO, from AbstractManagerImpl.java to MergedAnomalyResultManagerImpl.java.
2. Improvement: The method convertMergedAnomalyBean2DTO is a time consuming call because it needs to retrieve raw anomaly information from MySQL. If an anomaly page needs to show 10 merged anomalies and each of which has 4 raw anomalies, then this page makes 40 sequential MySQL queries.

This improvement creates a thread pool in the class level of MergedAnomalyResultManagerImpl.  The pool is used to retrieve the information of merged anomalies in parallel. Specifically, a thread is used to send the queries for a merged anomaly sequentially; moreover, at most 10 merged anomalies are processed concurrently.

Future Work: Current improvement uses additional threads, which consumes unnecessary resources. A possible improvement is using a single thread to send a batched MySQL query and get the information for all merged anomalies in one go.

title: Fix query issue for non-additive dataset
body:
Fix query issue for non-additive dataset, which throws java.util.ConcurrentModificationException occasionally.

The cause of this problem is that the query for non-additive (pre-computed) data are modified for adding additional filters for selecting pre-aggregated dimension value. If a query was used as a hash key and its filter is modified, then java.util.ConcurrentModificationException could be thrown when use the query as a hash key in the second time.

For example: A query Q is created --> Q is inserted to a hash map for exploiting the benefit of asynchronous queries --> Before send Q to Pinot, Q's filter is modified for non-additive dataset --> Q is used as the key to retrieve the asynchronous results --> ConcurrentModificationException is thrown when calculating the hashcode of Q.

The fix modifies the query's filter when the query is created, i.e., the first step of above example.

title: Add a limit on number of aggregation groups in query response.
body:
Queries with huge numbers of aggregation groups (millions range)
increase heap usage, and may lead to OOM. This change adds a
configurable limit on the number of aggregation groups, once query
execution crosses that number, it skips processing rest of the
documents, and returns truncated results.
1. Added a server config 'num.aggr.groups.limit', with a default value
   of 1 million.
2. GroupByExecutor will skip processing all remaining blocks (with a
   warning logged) once this limit is reached.

title: Limit number of groups in Aggregation-GroupBy query results.
body:
In AggregationGroupByOperator, we compute all groups at segment level.
This can cause high heap usage (or even OOM), if number of groups is
extremely large (multi-million groups range). This change limits the
number of groups returned by group by operator to a pre-defined size.
1. Added MAX_NUM_GROUPS_ALLOWED that defaults to 1M, and can be
   overwritten by unix env variable "pinot.max.aggr.groups".
2. ResultHolders switch from array mode to map mode, and start trimming
   groups (based on sort order) to cap the number of groups to the limit.
3. Benchmark results, on 5.5B records, 3.6M unique keys (per segment), 17 segments:
   - Takes 800 MB as opposed to > 2 GB, with similar latency.
   - With ~40M keys per segment, existing code runs OOM, where as this
     change can still perform within < 1 GB of memory.
4. Added unit tests for the same.

title: Pql for nonadditive (pre-aggregated) data
body:
- Change to PQL query: For nonadditive (pre-aggregated) dataset, we assume that there exists one dimension value "all", which is user configurable, that aggregates all dimension values on the corresponding dimension name. Therefore, if a user does not specify which value s/he is looking at at that dimension, then ThirdEye automatically append filters such as "thatDimensionName=all;" after the query. Consequently, ThirdEye would get the pre-aggregated value instead of SUM up the non-additive dimension.
- Change to UI: For nonadditive (pre-aggregated) dataset, the time granularity on the UI no longer provide useful meaning. For instance, if the time granularity of the pre-aggrated dataset is 1 hour, then it is meaningless to set the granularity to 1 day on the UI. Therefore, the user could set the true time granularity of the dataset in web app configuration to override the time granularity on the UI.

title: Adding a tool to migrate all datasets and configs to new design.
body:
Migration tool:
Reads all collections from pinot, which have a schema
For each collection
1) Extracts dimensions and timespec, to create dataset_config. Reads CollectionConfig to get metricAsDimension property. This check will go away once this tool becomes a pure pull from pinot instead of migrate existing.
2) Extracts metrics, to create metric_config. Reads CollectionConfig to get properties like inverse_metric, cell_size_expression, rollup_threshold
3) Reads CollectionConfig to get derived metrics. Compute derived expressions, by replacing the metric name with its id as “id<metric_id>”
4) Reads DashboardConfig to get custom dashboards, and create dashboard_config. This check will go away once this tool becomes a pure pull from pinot instead of migrate existing.
5) Creates Default_Dashboard for the collection, to serve as the basic collection view.

title: Support aggregations and aggregation group by on multi-value columns
body:
**Motivation & Use cases**
In Uber, we have use cases that required unique counting and group by both on multi-value columns. Say one user has multiple experiments, and multiple trips, instead of flattening both, I will explode my table row size. So I would like to do group by on the fly.
Also there is time series use case, which for the same dimension I need to access raw records as long as put on some aggregation functions. Think about I can do avg (trip_fare) for a user across arbitrary days window, if my data is daily "aggregated" to an array.
Like:
DAY | user_id | trip_fare
1 | aaa | [1,2,3,1]
2 | aaa | [1]
3 | aaa | [10]
avg(trip_fare) where DAY BETWEEN 1 AND 2 ==> 1.6
avg(trip_fare) where DAY BETWEEN 1 AND 3 ==> 6
avg(trip_fare) where DAY BETWEEN 2 AND 3 ==> 5.5

It's kind of trivial to support all the aggregation functions after unique counting is supported.
I also have use case which is under discussion to index gpslogs(Very huge, more than 6B points daily). There are a lot of redundancy to store user_id, trip_id multiple times in a single trip.


**Semantics for each of those functions.**
Lets describe the semantics for each of those functions.

For each function:
e.g we have a int array columnA with 100 rows, each row has two values [1,2].
count: This is not really implemented as we rewrite the count(col) to count(*) during query parser. But want to support it to return total number of entries for a selected column.

sum: sum up all the values in selected rows. sum(columnA) = 300

avg: sum/count(all the multi-values): avg(columnA) = 300/200 = 1.5

min/max: one value that is the min/max of all the values. min(columnA)=1, max(columnA) =2

minmaxRange: max-min. minmaxRange(columnA)=1

distinctCount: unique values across all the values, distinctCount(columnA) = 2

percentile: percentile based on all the values: percentile50(columnA) = 1;percentile90(columnA) = 2;

**Performance Impact**
Performance change for (existing) SV columns and (new) MV columns.
From my perf tests, this change doesn't impact SV columns perf, though there will be extra if check for each block, but I don't foresee any visible impact. For MV columns, we have predefined block, but need to read 1 row of multi-value for every selected docId. This will definitely be slow, but we will get benefit when we have filtering there. From data model part, we can compress multiple rows with same dimensions together and make metricsFields as multi-value fields(this is actually dimension and time based rollup). But we need to prepare it in Hadoop before loading data to Pinot.
